    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-10-30T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-10-30T18:00:00-05:00" n="354"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d354">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72119/8986</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Special Representative</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_HEM1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">House</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-10-30T23:00:00+00:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 30, 1918, 11 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received October 31, 4.36 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>13. For the President:</p>
                <p>At the meeting this afternoon practically entire time was consumed with a
                    discussion between <persName corresp="#p_LGD1">George</persName> and <persName
                        corresp="#p_CG2">Clemenceau</persName> as to who should accept the surrender
                    of the Turks—the British or the French admiral. Discussion was [most] bitter at
                    times and of course I did not participate in it. It was virtually agreed by
                    French, British, and Italians that the proposed answer to the President’s
                    communication as drafted by the British and as cabled you this morning, should
                    be adopted as the answer of the Allies, so far as Germany was concerned. It was
                    agreed that the terms of the military and naval armistice to be offered Austria
                    should be reviewed by the Allied generals and admirals, and when completed
                    should be transmitted direct through <persName corresp="#p_DGA1">General
                        Diaz</persName> to the Austrian commander-in-chief. This has the advantage
                    of avoiding political discussion respecting Italian and other claims before
                    capitulation of Austria [received]. [Armistice terms to be discussed?] by the
                    conference set for tomorrow at 11.30 at my headquarters, of <persName
                        corresp="#p_LGD1">George</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_CG2"
                        >Clemenceau</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_OVE1">Orlando</persName>,
                        <persName corresp="#p_FF1">Foch</persName> and myself. Full meeting of
                    Supreme War Council called for 3 p.m. tomorrow afternoon at Versailles.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HEM1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Edward House</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
